Ethylene hydrogenation on Pt thin films on Ni(1 0 0) surface
Abstract
From XPS and LEED studies, a layer-by-layer growth of Pt thin films is indicated up to 8 ML coverage on Ni(1 0 0) surface while a (1×1) structure changes to a disordered structure above 2 ML of Pt film thickness. The 1 ML Pt overlayer, as a model (1 0 0) surface of PtNi alloy single crystal, shows a considerable d-band narrowing probably due to the formation of an interface state with the Ni substrate. This induces weakly adsorbed hydrogen atoms and ethylene molecules and, as a result, the maximum evolution of ethane is observed around 200 K. A wide d-band extending to 6 eV binding energy is developed for Pt 6 ML film characteristic of bulk Pt electronic states, resulting in a similar surface chemistry of ethylene as on Pt(1 1 1) surface.
1. Introduction
Bimetallic catalysts are often used in industrial reactions in order to improve the activity and/or selectivity. The well-defined single crystal surfaces of binary alloys have been the object of numerous surface science studies investigating the correlation between the atomic level surface structure and the surface chemical reactivity for a better understanding of catalysis by alloys. Among these systems, it has been found that PtNi alloy single crystal surfaces show surface enrichment of one component, depending on the surface orientation; i.e., Pt enrichment at the first layer and Ni enrichment in the second layer for (1 0 0) and (1 1 1) surfaces, reverse order for (1 1 0) surface
[1]
,
[2]
,
[3]
. For the Pt0.5Ni0.5 (1 1 1) alloy surface, the outer layer with a quasi complete Pt layer exhibits very weakened chemisorptive properties compared to Pt(1 1 1), leading to more selective hydrogenation of butadiene toward butene
[4]
. This drastic change is interpreted to be associated with the presence of Ni in the sublayer which imposed a contraction of the bond lengths between the surface Pt atoms with alloying, due to the difference between the lattice parameters of Pt (3.924 Å) and Pt0.5Ni0.5 (3.755 Å).
As an alternative approach to better understand the fundamental properties and reactivity of PtNi bimetallic surfaces, a model bimetallic surface can be prepared by depositing Pt atoms onto Ni(1 0 0) surface as a substrate. This is a more direct way to correlate the change in the surface structure and related electronic states with chemical reactivity upon the addition of a second constituent. It is expected that the substrate can set an epitaxial relation to the overlayer which would cause severe strain as similar to the PtNi alloys having higher Ni bulk content, because the Ni substrate has an about 10% shorter lattice parameter than the Pt overlayers. This indicates that a metastable Pt(1 0 0) surface can be produced on the Ni substrate. It is well known that the pure Pt(1 0 0) surface reconstructs to a hexagonal surface layer resembling the structure of the Pt(1 1 1) surface. The influence of the topography of the substrate on the bonding and reactivity has been shown upon the adsorption of ethylene molecule on these surfaces; an ethylidyne intermediate is stabilized on the Pt(1 1 1) and reconstructed Pt(1 0 0) surfaces having the three-fold symmetry adsorption sites whereas a vinylidene is observed on the (1×1) Pt(1 0 0) surface
[5]
,
[6]
. Also, it has been shown that the rate for hydrogenation of ethylene can depend upon the surface orientation, i.e., it can present some sensitivity to the surface structure
[7]
.
In the present study, we have studied the adsorption of ethylene and hydrogen on Pt thin films grown on Ni(1 0 0) substrate in order to explore the relation between surface structure and its related electronic states and chemical reactivity of PtNi alloy in an atomic level.
2. Experimental
The experiments were performed in a stainless steel UHV chamber as described previously
[8]
. The system is equipped with facilities for X-ray and ultra-violet photoelectron spectroscopies (XPS and UPS) and low energy electron diffraction (LEED), a quadrupole mass spectrometer (QMS) with a cap shield for temperature programmed desorption (TPD), and two pulse valves for gas dosing. The system base pressure is 5×108 Pa. MgKα radiation (1253.6 eV) and He discharge lamp (21.2 eV) were used as photon sources for XPS and UPS. Photoelectrons were collected with a hemispherical analyzer. Its energy resolution was around 1 eV (XPS) and 0.5 eV (UPS). Angle-resolved UPS measurements at a given azimuth were accomplished by varying the angle between the sample normal and the detector direction. The angles were measured with respect to the sample normal. TPD measurements were made using the QMS in line of sight with the sample surface and using a linear heating rate of 23 K/s. The Ni(1 0 0) crystal can be cooled down to 100 K using liquid nitrogen or resistively heated to 1200 K. The temperature was measured by a chromelalumel thermocouple spotwelded to the side edge of the crystal.
The Ni(1 0 0) crystal was cleaned by repeated Ar ion sputtering and annealing at 1200 K procedures. Pt was evaporated from a tungsten filament containing a Pt wire by resistive heating on the clean Ni(1 0 0) surface kept at room temperature. Because of the carbon contamination resulting from each adsorption and subsequent TPD experiment, the Pt thin films were used as grown newly prepared for each experiment. Pt was removed by Ar ion sputtering and annealing at 1200 K. The cleanliness was checked by XPS. Research grade reactant gases purchased from Takachiho Co. were used without further purification.
3. Results and discussion
The growth mode of Pt thin films on Ni(1 0 0) surface was studied by XPS. The peak intensities of Pt 4f and Ni 2p core level photoelectrons taken at the collection angle of 36 from surface normal direction are shown as a function of deposition time at a constant deposition rate in
Fig. 1
. The intensities were normalized to the sum of these Pt and Ni peak areas in order to minimize the fluctuation during the measurements as shown in
Fig. 2
. The curves exhibit the exponential form for the Pt overlayer as well as the Ni substrate and can be approximated by a series of straight line segments expected for layer-by-layer growth. Assuming the equally separated Pt overlayer and the corrected escape depth in the direction for the analyzer by 1/cos 36, the layer-by-layer model is represented by the solid lines of
Fig. 2
. Reasonable agreement has been obtained in the first two layers of Pt. The deviation from the model is considered to be within an amount of uncertainty in XPS measurement. From these results, the attenuation coefficient of the Ni signal by a monolayer of Pt is found to be 0.64, leading to a mean free path for 400 eV electron of about 2.8 ML, which is a reasonable value compared with those reported in the literature
[9]
. The first two layers showed a (1×1) LEED pattern as dictated by substrate Ni surface, although further deposition of Pt atoms deteriorated the spots due to the (1×1) structure significantly. It indicates that a disordered layer-by-layer growth proceeds above 2 ML thickness.
