[13]
while the larger values of 5.96.4 eV are reported on Pt single crystal (1 0 0) and (1 1 1) surfaces
[14]
,
[15]
,
[16]
. This small value (5.2 eV) of the Pt overlayers is, therefore, indicative of the presence of the roughness on the surface, which is also in accordance with the disappearance of LEED pattern above 2 ML thick.
Fig. 3
shows angle-resolved photoemission with He I radiation to follow the change of the electronic structure of the Pt overlayers of 16 ML thicknesses on Ni(1 0 0) at normal emission. The Ni(1 0 0) substrate spectrum displays a peak around 0.8 eV below the Fermi level. The deposition of 1 ML Pt overlayer gives the peak with almost the same binding energy. Up to a Pt thickness of 3 ML a gradual development of a broad structure within 4 eV below the Fermi level. Increasing the film thickness up to 6 ML produced bulk Pt(1 1 1) structures at 1.5, 2.0, 2.6, and 4.2 eV binding energies. It would be expected that a larger dispersion for the Pt derived state is caused by the considerable overlap of the wave functions due to the reduced lattice constant. In order to examine the band dispersion in the surface parallel direction, angle-resolved UPS measurements have been carried out at the [0 1 0] azimuth of the surface as displayed in
Fig. 4
. It is observed that there is no significant difference in the band dispersion along the surface Brillouin zone of Σ line between the 1 ML Pt overlayer and the Ni substrate which lies within 2 eV from the Fermi level. On the other hand, a wide d-band structure extending to 6 eV binding energy characteristic of bulk three-dimensional Pt has developed for the 6 ML Pt films. It is, hence, considered that the Pt atoms in the first monolayer are bonding with the substrate Ni atoms rather than the neighboring Pt atoms. In this respect, this state resembles that observed as an interface state in the system Pt/Co(0 0 0 1) where the interface state has mainly the character of the overlayer (Pt 5d), despite its strong hybridization with the substrate
[17]
. These results strongly suggest that d-band narrowing in the 1 ML Pt overlayer is derived from reduced coordination of the surface Pt atoms and the charge flow upon the bonding to Ni atoms as an interface state. Consequently, the 1 ML Pt overlayer on Ni(1 0 0) surface can be regarded as the topmost two layers of an alloy with composition that is not far from Pt0.5Ni0.5.
