When we assume π-coordinated ethylene molecule present on the surface, the highest-occupied 1b2u (π) and the lowest unoccupied 1b3g (π*) molecular orbital should be primarily involved in the interaction with substrate. Since the unoccupied electronic structures in this system cannot be explored in the present study, adsorbate states are only discussed in the former molecular orbital and the electronic states of the Pt overlayer shown above to measure the hybridization of molecular orbital with substrate band structure. Considering the work function of the Pt overlayers, the energy level of molecular ethylene π orbital will be located around 5 eV below the Fermi level. Hence, this π orbital strongly interacts with the bottom of the Pt d-bands for the thicker Pt films as similar to bulk Pt(1 1 1). It is observed that a considerably strong bonding takes place in ethylene/Pt(1 1 1) system
[18]
. However, the d-band narrowing in the 1 ML Pt overlayer should lead to a weak overlap with the adsorbate orbital. These considerations will be exemplified in the TPD experiments shown below.
Before doing the experiment of temperature programmed reaction of ethylene with adsorbed hydrogen, we have measured the adsorption of hydrogen as one of adsorbates for ethylene hydrogenation. The thermal desorption spectra of H2 evolution from the Pt overlayers grown on the Ni(1 0 0) surface after hydrogen dosed below 150 K are summarized in
